['For starters you have a thread safety issue here. `onTouchEvent()` is called on the UI thread while `onDrawFrame()` is called by the GL thread. The issue is that you access `mTarget` in both methods and there is no thread safety handling involved. This can (and often will) cause unexpected and indeterminate results. You need to protect `mTarget` with a synchronization scheme.', 'As far as the face culling goes, if the above does not fix it (it would be an unrelated problem manifesting in odd ways) then there is a bug in the default GL state I have assigned to the library. There are other issues with this that I need to fix so please let me know if the issue isnt resolved by the thread safety and I will look into it.', 'Thank you for the fast reply ! 
So I just added/changed the following code

``` java
private static final Object OBJ_LOCK = new Object();

    @Override
    public void onTouchEvent(MotionEvent event) {
        super.onTouchEvent(event);

        synchronized (OBJ_LOCK) {
            mTarget.x =  ( event.getX()/getViewportWidth() ) * 2 - 1;
            mTarget.y = -((event.getY()/getViewportHeight()) * 2 - 1);
            mTarget.z = 1;
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void onDrawFrame(GL10 glUnused) {
        super.onDrawFrame(glUnused);

        synchronized (OBJ_LOCK) {
            float distance = mTarget.distanceTo(mLookAt);
            if( distance > 0.05f )
            {
                Vector3 step = Vector3.subtract(mTarget, mLookAt);
                step.multiply( 0.3f);
                mLookAt.add(step);

                mObject.setLookAt(mLookAt);

            }
        }
    }
```

Unfortunately the behavior is the same :/', 'ok then it is possible it is a bug. Is there anyway you can send a screenshot?', "Sure ! (I replaced the cube by an OBJ model)
Ok :+1: 
![frontface](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/5123957/882595/f8272630-f965-11e2-97ff-3bf7c4083d01.png)

Not Ok :(
![backface](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/5123957/882594/f7d352b2-f965-11e2-98ea-41b1d0b8174a.png)

For information when the culling is inverted, If I go to the settings then just go back, the culling is correct again. 
(I forgot to mentioned, I'm trying to make a Live Wallpaper)", "Yea that is definitely a culling problem. I'll add it to my growing list of things to fix but I'll try and address it sooner rather than later, possibly after I finish my current task. Just to be clear its fine when you load, you touch the screen and it breaks, then if you go to settings and back its fine again?", 'In the meantime, try setting the model to double sided and see if it alleviates the problem (it will also give me more info on the source of the problem).', "Exactly, once the model is loaded it's fine, I touch the screen and it breaks, then if I go to settings and back its fine again.

The funny thing is it looks like the behavior is different depending on how long I wait before touching the screen:
If I touch the screen like 15sec after the model is loaded -> it's fine
Between 1 and 15 sec -> culling inverted
Less than 1 sec (if I'm quick enough) -> black screen ! (and going to settings and back doesn't change anything)

Setting the model to double sided alleviates the culling problem but not the black screen. I think I can live with that for now if the performance hit is not too high.

I hope those informations will help you. Anyway thanks again for your support.", "Thanks for the added info, I'll see what I can find.", 'Eh... I thought I fixed the culling problem. What version is this? 0.9?', "Yea I may have jacked this up when I tried reducing go state changes though. I'm almost ready to get to looking at it. This is in master.", 'Hi @chocomega could you test this against the latest master? The lookAt code has changed, maybe this was fixed along the way :)', 'Closing this as stale. Please reopen if the problem persists.']

